This article is a statement by former President Barack Obama on the passing of Maya Angelou. Obama describes Angelou as a brilliant writer, a fierce friend, and a truly phenomenal woman. He highlights her many accomplishments, including being an author, poet, civil rights activist, and actress. Obama emphasizes that Angelou's true talent was storytelling, and her own difficult childhood experiences helped her inspire others to find hope. He also mentions that Angelou had a personal impact on him and his family, as his mother named his sister Maya after her. Obama concludes by stating that while Angelou's life may be over, her legacy will continue to inspire and celebrate the dawn she helped bring.